05850nam a22009015i 9783110673180DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020932268  a97831106731807 a10.1515/97831106731802doi  a(DE-B1597)535108  a(OCoLC)1158134519  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN212b.W34 2020 7aLIT0200002bisacsh1 aWagner, Eva Sabine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNarrativity, Coherence and Literariness :bA Theoretical Approach with Analyses of Laclos, Kafka and Toussaint /cEva Sabine Wagner. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XI, 638 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarratologia : Contributions to Narrative Theory ,x1612-8427 ;v68  aDiss.cKölnd2018.00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Coming to Terms with Complexity -- tPart A: Theory of Narrativity -- t1 Preliminary Epistemic Considerations: Narrativity and Narratology Between Order and Chaos -- t2 Problems of Defining Narrativity: Research Review and Systematisation -- t3 Narrativity and Coherence: Towards an Analysis of Literary Narrative Dynamics -- tPart B: Narrative Dynamics -- t4 “Narrative Projection”: Choderlos de Laclos’s Les Liaisons dangereuses -- t5 “Narrative Withdrawal”: Kafka’s Schloss -- t6 “Narrative resistance”: Jean-Philippe Toussaint’s novels -- tConcluding remarks: Elements of a ‘Rhizomatic’ Realignment of ‘Narrativity’ and Narratology -- tWorks Cited -- tTable of Figures -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe search for the defining qualities of narrative has produced an expansive range of definitions which, largely unconnected with each other, obscure the notion of “narrativity” rather than clarifying it.The first part of this study remedies this shortcoming by developing a graded macro model of narrativity which serves three aims. Firstly, it provides a structured overview of the field of narrative elements and processes. Secondly, it facilitates the classification of narratological approaches by locating them on different stages of narrativity. Finally, it focuses attention on narrative dynamics as interpretative processes by which readers seek to produce narrative coherence.The second part of this study identifies three different narrative dynamics which characterise Laclos’s "Dangerous Connections," Kafka’s "Castle" and Toussaint’s novels. Wagner bases her analyses of these dynamics not only on the texts themselves but also on the ways in which literary scholars imbue the texts with narrative coherence.This book provides a long overdue systematisation of the jumbled field of theories of narrativity and opens new perspectives on the difficult relationship between narrative theory and interpretation.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLiteraturexHistory and criticism. 0aNarration (Rhetoric) 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Comparative Literature.2bisacsh  aNarrativity.  anarrative coherence.  anarrative dynamics.  arhizome.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Engli